Q: How to print a diamond pattern using only two loops? A: <p>Use the Manhattan Distance from the center of the row or column.  If it is &lt;= to the radius to the center c then print a star.  Only two loops x and y.</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;
int main() { 
    int n,y,c,x; 
    cout&lt;&lt;&quot;\n\nEnter number of rows: &quot;;
    cin&gt;&gt;n;
    n|=1; // make odd
    c = n/2; 
    for (y=0;y&lt;n;y++) { 
      for (x=0;x&lt;n;x++) { 
         // calc Manhattan Distance to center
         // &lt;= solid diamond 
         // == Hollow 
         // &gt;= Box Diamond
         cout&lt;&lt;((abs(y-c)+abs(x-c) &lt;= c) ? '*':' '); 
      }
      cout&lt;&lt;endl; 
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Output:</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>$ g++ -o test diamondTwo.cpp 
$ ./test


Enter number of rows: 11
     *     
    ***    
   *****   
  *******  
 ********* 
***********
 ********* 
  *******  
   *****   
    ***    
     *     
</code></pre>

Q: How do you create a `preg_match` with plural s and &#39; A: <p>Basic pattern for plural 's' and apostrophe</p>
<p>To match words that can end with a plural 's' or an apostrophe:</p>
<pre><code>// Pattern: matches word optionally ending with 's' or apostrophe
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+['']?s?$/&quot;;

// Examples:
preg_match($pattern, &quot;cat&quot;);      // matches
preg_match($pattern, &quot;cats&quot;);     // matches
preg_match($pattern, &quot;cat's&quot;);    // matches
preg_match($pattern, &quot;cats'&quot;);    // matches (plural possessive)
</code></pre>
<p>More specific patterns</p>
<p><strong>Match words with optional plural 's' or possessive apostrophe:</strong></p>
<pre><code>// Word, optionally followed by apostrophe, optionally followed by 's'
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+(['']?s?|s['']?)$/&quot;;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Match plural OR possessive (not both):</strong></p>
<pre><code>// Word ending with just 's' (plural) OR word with apostrophe (possessive)
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+(['']s?|s)$/&quot;;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Allow apostrophe anywhere (for contractions):</strong></p>
<pre><code>// Word that may contain apostrophe and may end with 's'
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+([''][a-zA-Z]*)?s?$/&quot;;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>More strict: plural 's' OR possessive apostrophe:</strong></p>
<pre><code>// Either: word + s (plural) OR word + apostrophe + s (possessive)
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+(['']s|s)$/&quot;;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Common use case examples:</strong></p>
<pre><code>// Match names with apostrophes (O'Brien, O'Connor)
$pattern = &quot;/^[A-Z]['']?[a-z]+$/&quot;;

// Match plural words (cats, dogs, boxes) - including words ending in x/ch/sh which add 'es'
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+(s|es|xes)?$/&quot;;

// Match possessive forms (John's, cats', children's)
$pattern = &quot;/^[a-zA-Z]+['']s?$/&quot;;
</code></pre>
